>Dear all,Just wanted to warn people of =
kundalini syndrome based on my recent experience of a patient of mine.I am =
doing a psychiatry job at present, and have been involved in the care of so=
meone who seems to think she has had a spontaneous awakening of their kunda=
lini since childhood. This has involved out-of-body experiences and surges =
of energy in the body. She is not of Indian origin and had never heard of k=
undalini until her symptoms started and she searched for an explanation. We=
 have not been able to find anything physically wrong with her (all tests n=
ormal)- so it might be that this is due to deranged kundalini. Many people =
we call mentally ill describe themselves as having a spiritual crisis, or u=
nwanted spontaneous kundalini awakening- this has triggered interest and re=
search into this topic in mainstream psychiatry. Unfortunately these patien=
ts are not well-understood by western medicine, and as we have no treatment=
s for deranged kundalini, we
 struggle to help them.Many yogis try to forci=
bly waken the kundalini. My experience with this lady confirmed my feeling =
that kundalini should not be forcibly wakened. This woman wants to kill her=
self at times because the suffering from the deranged energy is so bad. She=
 feels it will consume her, and it is something she cannot escape from.I wo=
ndered what solution there could be to her problem. The logical one was to =
pray to the Divine Mother, who manifests as the kundalini to relieve the su=
ffering of this woman- and either cure her, or give her the strength to bea=
r this. May I request that the good samaritans among you pray for her, and =
for others like her (whom we may not know of)- their suffering really is pi=
tiable. And let us be careful in our sadhana so as not to end up in this si=
tuation ourselves. Perhaps this is why the bhakti marga is the safest. It i=
s perhaps safest to say "let me be your instrument" and leave the kundalini=
 rising bit to God's
 will.Om Dum Durgayai NamahaAparna 
